Springboot with RAG
   First let's understand how the traditional LLM model is working. So here we have the user that is asking a question to the LLMs like OpenAI, Gemini and AzureAI. So whenever the user asks a
question to the LLM, it looks up and queries the pre-trained data of the LLM. Usually this data is  historical training data and it is not up to date with the current affairs. This is one of
the problem with the traditional LLMs because they rely on historical training data and not update  with the current data and they also have no knowledge about our own knowledge base like our internal documentation etc. 
  So if you have a huge internal documentation and you want to use the capabilities of LLMs to get a nice summary out of your internal documentation then it is not possible with the traditional LLM way. So that's why a new AI technique called as retrieval augmented generation was introduced. 
  So it is nothing but a technique that is used to retrieve external information like our knowledge base like PDFs, HTML or CSV or text documents and using that information and we combine the logical reasoning capabilities of LLM and then we generate some accurate responses to the user questions. 

Retrieval augmented generation
   So the user first uploads their knowledge based document like a PDF or text document. And then they upload this document to our application which is enhanced with this RAG capabilities. And then the applications processes this document and then stores this data in the form of vectors in a vector database. 
  A vector database is a specialized database like SQL relational database and non-reational
database that stores data in the form of vector. A vector is nothing but a mathematical representation of the human readable text. We have different kinds of database to store this vector data like pinecone, chroma, pg vector, maria db, redis, cassandra etc. So to fulfill the user queries, our application will perform a similarity search based on the given question to the vector database and then we get the response back from the database and this response is sent as an LLM prompt and then our LLMs will give back the answer. 
   So to perform the steps 2, 3 and 4 we have something called as a data injection pipeline. So we have our user document and our application will splits that document into different chunks and then it will convert these chunks into something called as an embedding. An embedding is a type of
vector that is used to represent the data in a format that is understandable for LLMs. So we need to essentially convert this text of chunk into embeddings and then store it into the vector database. Next we retrieve this embeddings and then we provide it along with the user prompt to 
the llms. 

