Implementations
Both ChatMemory and ChatMemoryRepository are interfaces. Spring AI provides default implementations:

1. MessageWindowChatMemory – Default implementation of ChatMemory. It keeps the last 20 messages by default.
2. InMemoryChatMemoryRepository – Stores messages in memory using a ConcurrentHashMap where we key as conversationid and value as List of messages. Data is lost when the app restarts.
3. JdbcChatMemoryRepository – Stores messages in a database using JDBC.
4. You can also create custom implementations by implementing these interfaces.

Why limit memory size?
Because all stored messages are included in the prompt sent to the LLM. More messages = more tokens = higher cost and slower response. So, the default limit is 20 messages.

Advisors for Memory
To use memory effectively, Spring AI provides Advisors that automatically inject conversation history into prompts:

MessageChatMemoryAdvisor – Adds messages with roles in prompt(system, user, assistant).
PromptChatMemoryAdvisor – Adds messages as plain text (useful if the LLM doesn’t support roles).
VectorStoreChatMemoryAdvisor – For vector-based memory using vector databases.

These advisors intercept requests and add memory context before sending them to the LLM.

