Manage User Sessions - How multiple users can interact with LLM
      Previously we are storing messages using MessageWindowChatMemory—how many messages to store in memory or in a database, and what the strategy should be.
    When we were using Message Window Chat Memory, internally it was using InMemoryChatMemoryRepository. What was this doing? It was automatically storing messages in memory temporarily—meaning, as long as the application was running, the messages stayed. Once you stopped the application, the messages were deleted.

Now, there are two problems here:
1. Our application interacts with an LLM (Large Language Model) to get responses or use its intelligence.
2. Users of our application are not limited to one person. There can be multiple users, and each user should have their own message history.

That means sessions should be separate for each user. For example, if User 1 and User 2 are using the app, each should have their own message history maintained. Currently, we can only maintain one message history. Let’s understand the problem with an example before solving it.

Suppose User 1 runs: http://localhost:2222/chat?q=My name is Harsh

This message gets stored in memory using the concepts we discussed (via InMemoryChatMemoryRepository).

If User 1 then runs: http://localhost:2222/chat?q=What is my name?

The system correctly responds: “Your name is Harsh.”

But now, if another user (User 2) uses the app and runs in browser:
http://localhost:2222/chat?q=My name is Ankit

The system responds: “Hello Ankit, nice to meet you.”

Now, if User 1 again runs: http://localhost:2222/chat?q=What is my name?

The system incorrectly says: “Your name is Ankit.”

This happens because we are not managing sessions per user—the message history is shared.
 
ctrl+shift+T - ChatMemory, MessageWindowChatMemory

Currently, we are using Chat Memory to define strategies, and its implementation is MessageWindowChatMemory. By default, it stores 20 messages (maxMessages = 20). These messages are sent to the LLM to provide context for generating responses. This is important because sending too many messages increases token consumption, so we keep it limited.

Internally, MessageWindowChatMemory uses ChatMemoryRepository, and we are using InMemoryChatMemoryRepository. This stores data in a ConcurrentHashMap with a key-value pair:

Key = conversationId
Value = list of messages

Currently, the default conversationId is “default”, so all messages go under this single key. To fix this, we need to separate messages based on conversationId. That means, for each user, we will create a unique conversationId and store messages accordingly.

How do we do this?
We can take the conversationId from the user—like a userId—and pass it in the request header. For example, in the controller, we can use @RequestHeader to read the userId. This userId will act as the conversationId. If the same userId comes again, we’ll fetch the same session; otherwise, a new session will be created.

	@GetMapping("/chat")
	public ResponseEntity<String> chat(@RequestParam(value = "q", required = true) String query,@RequestHeader("userId") String userId) {
		String str = chatClient.prompt()
				.advisors(advisorSpec -> advisorSpec.param(ChatMemory.CONVERSATION_ID,userId))			
				.system(system -> system.text(this.systemMessage))
				.user(user -> user.text(this.userMessage).param("concept", query)).call().content();
		return ResponseEntity.ok(str);
		
	}

Internally, Spring AI will use this conversationId to store messages in the ConcurrentHashMap under separate keys for each user.

