LLM will “decide” when to use a tool.


Tool calling allows AI models to augment their capabilities by calling external tools. These external tools generally serve two main purposes:
1. Information Retrieval
Fetching information such as the current date, weather, database counts, etc.
2. Action Taking
Performing actions like setting an alarm, turning on a bulb, creating a table in a database, inserting data, and so on.

How do we implement this?
    In Spring AI, we can define a method as a tool. Spring AI does a lot of heavy lifting behind the scenes—it provides built-in support for specifying tools. With this support, we can declare the available tools so the AI model knows they exist. When the model decides a tool is needed, Spring AI will call it and then pass the result back to the chat model. The chat model uses that result to generate the final response.
    Sometimes, we return the tool’s output directly to the user without sending it back to the chat model. But the basic flow of tool calling usually works as described above.

Two Ways to Wire Tools in Spring AI
We have two main ways to work with tools:
1. Declarative approach
Use annotations (e.g., @Tool) to declare tools and make them discoverable to chat models.
2. Programmatic approach
A more advanced, low-level callback method


1. We’ll create a tool that returns the current date and time. So we Create the tool. Use Spring AI’s @Tool annotation (from org.springframework.ai.tool) to describe the tool, 
e.g.: Description: “Get the current date and time in the user’s time zone.”
If your tool accepts parameters, describe them using @ToolParam so the LLM knows what to pass when it calls the tool.

@Slf4j
public class SimpleDateTimeTool {

    @Tool(description = "Get the current date and time in users zone.")
    public String getCurrentDateTime() {
        log.info("Tool calling");
        log.info("Get the current date and time in users zone.");
        return LocalDateTime.now()
                .atZone(LocaleContextHolder.getTimeZone().toZoneId())
                .toString();
    }
}

2. Attach the tool to the ChatClient inside service prg- Pass an instance of SimpleDateTimeTool to the ChatClient so the LLM becomes aware of the tool

public String chat(String q) {
		return chatClient.prompt().tools(new SimpleDateTimeTool()).user(q).call().content();
	}

After this, when the LLM decides it needs the current date/time, Spring AI will invoke your tool, capture its output, and either return it directly or feed it back into the model to produce the final, enriched response.

