Model Context Protocol (MCP) 
    Most people are building AI‑powered applications today. No matter what kind of product it is, AI is integrated into almost everything now.
    When we build a Spring Boot application and want to add AI‑powered capabilities to it, we need to use an additional module — Spring AI. Spring AI is the module that helps our Spring Boot application interact with LLMs. So now, this application is AI‑powered.

What does AI‑powered mean?
It means the application has a brain.
And whose brain is it?
That brain is the LLM.

Since we are using Spring AI, our application already has access to an LLM, and whenever required, Spring AI can interact with that LLM.
That’s why we can say that the application you see here is an AI‑powered application.

what is the problem with this setup?
    We have a brain (ie) the LLM. Now, if a query comes into our application, what can the LLM do?

The LLM can: Understand the query, Interpret its intent,Process the input logically

But having a brain alone is not enough. Along with having a brain, our application must be able to interact with external resources or external systems. So Our AI‑powered application was not able to use external systems.

What is external system?
   External systems include almost everything that exists outside your application, such as:
- Database‑related tools
- Data tools like postgres sql, google drive
- Productivity tools like maps, slack
- Any external application

So our application cannot directly interact with these external systems.
Earlier we handle this communication using concepts like Function calling, tool calling etc

But the problem is:
- They are limited
- They cause vendor lock‑in
- They are not standardized

You can use them, but they are not a standard way of doing things.

Why We Need a Standard
   What we really need is a standard mechanism that allows our AI‑powered applications to interact with external systems. So
- Our AI‑powered application already has a brain
- It already uses an LLM
- But it is not capable of interacting with external systems

And if an application cannot interact with external systems, then obviously it will not be able to do any meaningful real‑world work which is becomes a serious limitation.

Introducing Model Context Protocol (MCP)
     Because of this exact problem, a new protocol was created which defines set of rules and regulations. And this protocol is called the Model Context Protocol (MCP). Now we have:
- Defined rules
- Defined regulations
- A common standard

With the help of these rules and regulations:
✅ Our AI‑powered application can now interact with external resources
✅ It can now use external tools

So we define MCP as:
   A standard that allows AI‑powered applications to interact with external tools.

Standard means:
- Basic rules
- Common regulations
- A protocol that works for everyone

If you have an external tool, using MCP:
- You can expose that tool
- Your AI‑powered application can consume and use it

So, in simple terms: MCP is an open‑source protocol that allows AI‑powered applications to interact with external systems.

Real‑World AI Examples 
 If you look at:
- ChatGPT Desktop
- Claude Desktop

These are also AI‑powered applications. And they also interact with external systems. For example:

- You search something in chat. It fetches data from Google
It retrieves data from the web

Now, the LLM itself does not have this data. The LLM only has the knowledge it was trained on It does not natively have Google data or live internet data.
So how does it fetch live data?
✅ Because it has external tools available
✅ And through those tools, it accesses external systems

Example:
   Think of MCP like a USB‑C port for AI applications.

If you search for “USB‑C”, you’ll see that USB‑C has become a standard connector.
If a device has a USB‑C port, it means:
- It can connect universally with other devices
- It follows a common standard

Earlier, things were very different. Some phones used:
- Lightning cables
- Micro‑USB
- USB‑B
- Other proprietary connectors

Because of this, devices could not easily connect with each other.
For example, if a friend came to my house with an iPhone using a Lightning cable, and I didn’t have a Lightning cable, then there was no way to charge it. That means Lightning was not universal.

Now, USB‑C has become a universal connector. You can find USB‑C in:
- Laptops
- Mobile phones
- Tablets
- iPads

Because USB‑C is a standard, all these devices can easily connect with each other.

In exactly the same way: MCP has become a universal standard for AI applications. You can think of MCP as:

- A universal protocol
- A standard interface
- A common connector for AI applications

Just like USB‑C enables devices to connect with each other, MCP enables AI applications to interact with external systems.

What MCP enables ?
Using MCP:
- AI agents (AI applications) can use external systems
- They can integrate with services like Google Calendar
- They can access productivity tools
- They can use design tools like Figma
- They can generate entire web applications using external designs

Why does MCP matter?
   If your AI‑powered application cannot access external tools:
- It won’t be able to solve real‑world problems
- Nobody is interested in asking it only “2 + 2” or just passing static information

An LLM has limited knowledge. It only knows what it was trained on. Without external systems:
- It cannot access real‑time data
- It cannot perform real‑world actions

Benefits of MCP
✅ For Developers

Reduced development time
Reduced complexity
No vendor lock‑in
Standardized integration

✅ For AI Applications & Agents

Much more powerful capabilities
Real‑world task execution

This means real use cases cannot be solved without external interaction.


Core MCP Architecture Concepts 
There are three key participants in the MCP architecture:

MCP Host
MCP Client
MCP Server

These three components form the foundation of MCP.

MCP consists of two layers:
- Data Layer
- Transport Layer
The Transport Layer supports two mechanisms:
- Stdio Transport
- Streamable Transport

Why Another Protocol When HTTP Already Exists? 
    MCP is specifically designed for AI applications. If you are building AI‑powered applications, and you want to interact with external tools and systems, MCP is the best‑suited protocol.

How MCP Actually Works
     Key Components in MCP Architecture

1. External Systems - These can be anything:
- Databases
- Data tools
- Google Drive
- Slack
- Maps
- Any third‑party application

2. LLM (The Brain)
The LLM is responsible for:
- Understanding the user’s query
- Reasoning
- Decision making

3. MCP Server
- All tools are defined and exposed here
- The actual business logic and real code execute here
- Tools interact with external systems

4. Spring Boot AI Application (MCP Host)
This application contains:
- Spring AI
- LLM integration
- MCP Client
This application acts as the MCP Host.

MCP Client–Server Architecture
MCP follows a client–server architecture.
1. MCP Client
The MCP client:
- Acts as a translator
- Knows the format of requests and responses
- Fetches metadata about available tools from the MCP server
- Creates requests and sends them using the MCP protocol

2. MCP Host
Any AI application that uses one or more MCP clients is called an MCP Host.
Your Spring Boot + Spring AI application is the MCP Host.

3. MCP Server
- Stores tool definitions
- Executes real logic
- Calls external systems
- Returns responses

End‑to‑End Flow 
Let’s understand the complete flow.
Step 1: User Request
A user sends a request containing a query.

Step 2: LLM Understanding

Spring AI forwards the query to the LLM
The LLM understands the intent
The LLM decides what action is required


Step 3: Tool Metadata Already Available
Before this:

MCP client has already fetched all available tools from MCP server.
Tool metadata is already cached

Step 4: Tool Selection

Based on the LLM’s response
MCP client selects the correct tool
Tool selection is done on the client side

Step 5: Tool Invocation

MCP client creates the request
Sends it to MCP server using MCP protocol
MCP server executes real code
MCP server interacts with external systems


Step 6: Response Handling

MCP server sends the result back
MCP client receives the response
The application forwards the result to the LLM
LLM converts it into natural language


Step 7: Final User Response
The AI‑powered application sends a user‑friendly response.


