Why use MCP resources and Why not RAG?
     RAG also known as Retrieval Augmented Generation, is a technique where we take documents and split them into chunks, convert those chunks into vector embeddings. Store them in a vector database like Pinecone or Weaviate. And when a user asks a question, we embed the question, search the vector database for similar chunks using semantics similarity. And pass those relevant chunks to LLM as a context. The LLM generates an answer based on that context.

Advantages of RAG. 
1. RAG is incredibly powerful. When we want AI to work with a large collection of documents
2. It can search and retrieve the semantically similar content, even if the wording is different.  
3. It a great choice for building Q&A systems, or for retrieving knowledge from big text repositories with accuracy and speed. 

Disadvantage
1. First is infrastructure overhead, to make RAG work, we need embeddings, chunking, a vector database, and a full document ingestion pipeline. That's a lot of setup so that AI can read and recall information.
2. Real-time updates are also difficult. If a document changes, we must re-chunk, re-embed, and update the index. For large documents, this takes times, so RAG isn't ideal when you need instant updates.
3. Loss of structure. Chunking breaks documents into small pieces, meaning
the model can lose context, like page order, section hierarchy, or relationships
between parts of the content. And it is not ideal for structured
or dynamic data. RAG works best with static unstructured text,
for things like database records, API responses or fast changing sensor data, it doesn't
shine as much. This is where MCP

When to use RAG or MCP?
1. RAG is the right choice when you're dealing with a large number of documents, and needs semantic search (IE) the AI can find context based on meaning and not exact wording. It's well suited for relatively static information, like knowledge base or Q&A systems, and it helps reduce token usage by retrieving only the most relevant chunks. 

2.  MCP resources make more sense when your data is smaller, constantly changing or needs real-time access. It works great with structured formats like JSON, logs or CSV files. And since the AI reads the entire context instead of chunks, it keeps full context without complicated infrastructure. 

